Definitions.
In this Act, unless the context otherwise requires,—
(a) "Competent Authority" means,—
(i) in the case of a Minister of the Union or a Member of Parliament or a Group 'A' officer in the Central Government or in a body or Board or corporation or authority or company or society or trust or autonomous body (by whatever name called) established, constituted or incorporated under a Central Act or financed or controlled by the Central Government,— the Central Vigilance Commission;
(ii) in the case of a Member of the Legislature of a State,— the Lokayukta or the Upa-Lokayukta established under a law made by the State Legislature, or in the absence of such Lokayukta or Upa-Lokayukta, the State Vigilance Commission;
(iii) in the case of a Group 'A' officer in the State Government or in a body or Board or corporation or authority or company or society or trust or autonomous body (by whatever name called) established, constituted or incorporated under a State Act or financed or controlled by the State Government,— the Lokayukta or Upa-Lokayukta of the State or in the absence of such Lokayukta or Upa-Lokayukta, the State Vigilance Commission;
(iv) in the case of any other officer or employee of the Central Government,— the Central Vigilance Commission;
(v) in the case of any other officer or employee of the State Government,— the State Vigilance Commission;
(b) "disclosure" means a complaint relating to,—
(i) an attempt to commit or commission of an offence under the Prevention of Corruption Act, 1988 (49 of 1988);
(ii) wilful misuse of power or wilful misuse of discretion against public interest by a public servant;
(iii) an attempt to commit or commission of a criminal offence by a public servant;
(c) "public servant" means any person who is or has been—
(i) a member of either House of Parliament, or of the Legislature of a State;
(ii) a member of any local authority;
(iii) any person in the service or pay of the Central Government, a State Government, a local authority, or a body or authority or company or society or trust or organisation (by whatever name called) owned, controlled or substantially financed by the Central Government or a State Government or a local authority;
(iv) any person remunerated by the Central Government or a State Government by way of fees or commission for the performance of any public duty;
(v) a Judge of any court;
(vi) a person in the service or pay of any court;
(vii) any person holding an office by virtue of which he is authorized or required to perform any public duty;
(d) "victimisation" means any action taken or attempted to be taken by the public servant against a complainant or any witness or any other person rendering assistance in an inquiry under this Act;
(e) "Vigilance Commission" means the Central Vigilance Commission constituted under sub-section (1) of section 3 of the Central Vigilance Commission Act, 2003 (45 of 2003), or, as the case may be, the State Vigilance Commission.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Powers of Competent Authority.
(1) On receipt of a disclosure under section 4, the Competent Authority shall call for the explanation of the public servant and inquire or cause an inquiry to be made into the disclosure in such manner as may be prescribed.
(2) For the purpose of inquiry under sub-section (1), the Competent Authority shall have all the powers of a civil court under the Code of Civil Procedure, 1908 (5 of 1908) while trying a suit, in respect of the following matters, namely:—
(a) summoning and enforcing the attendance of any person and examining him on oath;
(b) requiring the discovery and production of any document;
(c) receiving evidence on affidavits;
(d) requisitioning any public record or copy thereof from any court or office;
(e) issuing commissions for the examination of witnesses and documents;
(f) any other matter which may be prescribed.
(3) The Competent Authority shall, within a period of thirty days from the date of receipt of a disclosure, cause an inquiry to be made in respect of the disclosure received by it.
(4) If the Competent Authority is of the opinion that the public servant against whom the complaint is made is prima facie guilty of corruption or misuse of power, it shall recommend appropriate action to the public authority or public servant's appointing authority.
(5) The Competent Authority shall keep the identity of the complainant secret to the extent possible, shall not reveal the identity of the complainant and shall ensure that no hardship is caused to the complainant.
